#:proof{:extraction {:phases {:execute "1. **(I ⇒ II)** If \\(R\\) is a PID, every nonzero ideal is generated by a single element of minimal norm. That makes \\(R\\) a Euclidean domain, hence a GCD domain, hence a unique factorization domain: every nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles, and the factorization is unique up to units (see any algebra text, e.g. Dummit–Foote Thm. 8.4).\n\n2. **(II ⇒ IV)** Let \\(R\\) be a UFD with field of fractions \\(K\\), and suppose \\(\\alpha = a/b \\in K\\) is integral over \\(R\\) with coprime \\(a,b \\in R\\). Plugging \\(\\alpha\\) into a monic polynomial with coefficients in \\(R\\) gives an equation\n   \\[\n   (a/b)^m + c_{m-1}(a/b)^{m-1} + \\cdots + c_0 = 0.\n   \\]\n   Clearing denominators shows \\(b \\mid a^m\\), but in a UFD an irreducible dividing \\(b\\) cannot divide \\(a\\) (they were coprime). Therefore \\(b\\) has to be a unit, so \\(\\alpha \\in R\\). Thus \\(R\\) is integrally closed in \\(K\\).\n\n3. **(II ⇏ I)** Take \\(k[x,y]\\), the polynomial ring in two variables over a field \\(k\\). Adjoining indeterminates to a UFD preserves unique factorisation, so this ring is a UFD. But the ideal \\((x,y)\\) cannot be generated by a single polynomial—any one generator would have to divide both \\(x\\) and \\(y\\), which is impossible—so \\(k[x,y]\\) is not a PID.\n\n4. **(II ⇏ III)** Consider \\(k[x_1,x_2,x_3,\\dots]\\), the polynomial ring in countably many indeterminates over \\(k\\). Again, adjoining indeterminates preserves the UFD property, so the ring is a UFD. However the chain\n   \\[\n   (x_1) \\subsetneq (x_1,x_2) \\subsetneq (x_1,x_2,x_3) \\subsetneq \\cdots\n   \\]\n   never stabilises, so the ring is not Noetherian.\n\n5. **(III ⇏ I)** Return to \\(k[x,y]\\). Hilbert’s basis theorem says polynomial rings in finitely many variables over Noetherian rings are Noetherian, so \\(k[x,y]\\) is Noetherian. From step (3) we know it is not a PID.\n\n6. **(c)** The quadratic integer ring \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is a classic example of a domain that is not a UFD: \\(6 = 2\\cdot 3 = (1+\\sqrt{-5})(1-\\sqrt{-5})\\), and those two factorizations are irreducible and inequivalent.\n\n---"}, :dependency-graph [{:lemma "unparsed-lemma", :formal-dependency "1. **(I ⇒ II)** If \\(R\\) is a PID, every nonzero ideal is generated by a single element of minimal norm. That makes \\(R\\) a Euclidean domain, hence a GCD domain, hence a unique factorization domain: every nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles, and the factorization is unique up to units (see any algebra text, e.g. Dummit–Foote Thm. 8.4).", :informal-dependency nil, :why-this-now nil, :lean-type "1. **(I ⇒ II)** If \\(R\\) is a PID, every nonzero ideal is generated by a single element of minimal norm. That makes \\(R\\) a Euclidean domain, hence a GCD domain, hence a unique factorization domain: every nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles, and the factorization is unique up to units (see any algebra text, e.g. Dummit–Foote Thm. 8.4).", :notes "1. **(I ⇒ II)** If \\(R\\) is a PID, every nonzero ideal is generated by a single element of minimal norm. That makes \\(R\\) a Euclidean domain, hence a GCD domain, hence a unique factorization domain: every nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles, and the factorization is unique up to units (see any algebra text, e.g. Dummit–Foote Thm. 8.4)."} {:lemma "unparsed-lemma", :formal-dependency "2. **(II ⇒ IV)** Let \\(R\\) be a UFD with field of fractions \\(K\\), and suppose \\(\\alpha = a/b \\in K\\) is integral over \\(R\\) with coprime \\(a,b \\in R\\). Plugging \\(\\alpha\\) into a monic polynomial with coefficients in \\(R\\) gives an equation\n   \\[\n   (a/b)^m + c_{m-1}(a/b)^{m-1} + \\cdots + c_0 = 0.\n   \\]\n   Clearing denominators shows \\(b \\mid a^m\\), but in a UFD an irreducible dividing \\(b\\) cannot divide \\(a\\) (they were coprime). Therefore \\(b\\) has to be a unit, so \\(\\alpha \\in R\\). Thus \\(R\\) is integrally closed in \\(K\\).", :informal-depe