rn to \\(k[x,y]\\). Hilbert’s basis theorem says polynomial rings in finitely many variables over Noetherian rings are Noetherian, so \\(k[x,y]\\) is Noetherian. From step (3) we know it is not a PID.", :notes "5. **(III ⇏ I)** Return to \\(k[x,y]\\). Hilbert’s basis theorem says polynomial rings in finitely many variables over Noetherian rings are Noetherian, so \\(k[x,y]\\) is Noetherian. From step (3) we know it is not a PID."} {:lemma "unparsed-lemma", :formal-dependency "6. **(c)** The quadratic integer ring \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is a classic example of a domain that is not a UFD: \\(6 = 2\\cdot 3 = (1+\\sqrt{-5})(1-\\sqrt{-5})\\), and those two factorizations are irreducible and inequivalent.\n\n---", :informal-dependency nil, :why-this-now nil, :lean-type "6. **(c)** The quadratic integer ring \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is a classic example of a domain that is not a UFD: \\(6 = 2\\cdot 3 = (1+\\sqrt{-5})(1-\\sqrt{-5})\\), and those two factorizations are irreducible and inequivalent.\n\n---", :notes "6. **(c)** The quadratic integer ring \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is a classic example of a domain that is not a UFD: \\(6 = 2\\cdot 3 = (1+\\sqrt{-5})(1-\\sqrt{-5})\\), and those two factorizations are irreducible and inequivalent.\n\n---"}], :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 1, :dep-graph-count 6, :arse-count 0}, :classification :proved, :reclassification-reason "Post-hoc: zero sorry with substantive declarations", :output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (PID/UFD/Noetherian/integrally closed domains, plus the requested counterexamples, are explicitly referenced in both artifacts) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the main Lean target only assumes “R is a PID” and concludes integrally closed; helper lemmas state example properties without presupposing them) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (each formal target is a substantive ring-theoretic statement) · notes: helper lemmas tie directly to the counterexamples required in (b)–(c), so the plan cleanly separates implications from examples.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Map the logical implications PID ⇒ UFD ⇒ integrally closed and collect standard counterexamples witnessing the missing arrows among PID, UFD, and Noetherian domains.\"\n :terms [{:name \"principal ideal domain\"\n          :meaning \"Every ideal of R is generated by a single element.\"\n          :needed-because \"The PID hypothesis is the starting point of the implication chain and is the property we must negate in two counterexamples.\"}\n         {:name \"unique factorization domain\"\n          :meaning \"Each nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles uniquely up to associates.\"\n          :needed-because \"The middle node in the chain and a property satisfied by our first two counterexamples.\"}\n         {:name \"Noetherian domain\"\n          :meaning \"Every ascending chain of ideals stabilizes (equivalently, every ideal is finitely generated).\"\n          :needed-because \"Used in the failed implications II⇒III and III⇒I, so we need rings that are/aren’t Noetherian appropriately.\"}\n         {:name \"integrally closed domain\"\n          :meaning \"R contains every element of its fraction field that is integral over R.\"\n          :needed-because \"This is the endpoint in (a), so we need a clean route from UFDs to integrally closed domains.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"IsPrincipalIdealRing.isUniqueFactorizationMonoid\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Standard textbook fact that PIDs are UFDs.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Settles the first arrow in (a).\"\n             :lean-target \"∀ {R} [CommRing R] [IsDomain R], IsPrincipalIdealRing R → UniqueFactorizationMonoid R\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Available: Mathlib already provides `IsPrincipalIdealRing.isUniqueFactorizationMonoid`.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"UniqueFactorizationMonoid.isIntegrallyClosed\"\n             :informal-dependency \"UFDs are integrally closed (since height-one primes are principal).\"\n             :why-this-now \"Completes the chain II ⇒ IV.\"\n             :lean-target \"∀ {R} [CommRing R] [IsDomain R], UniqueFactorizationMonoid R → IsIntegrallyClosed R\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Available via `UniqueFactorizationMonoid.isIntegrallyClosed`.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"PolynomialRing.twoVars.notPID\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Use k[x,y] over a field: it is a UFD but not a PID.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Provides II ⇏ I.\"\n             :lean-target \"∀ (k) [Field k], UniqueFactorizationMonoid (Polynomial k (Polynomial k)) ∧ ¬ IsPrincipalIdealRing (Polynomial k (Polynomial k))\"\n             :mathlib-status \"UFD part exists; non-PID proof requires exhibiting the ideal (x,y).\"}\n            {:id :s4\n             :formal-dependency \"PolynomialRing.infiniteVars.notNoetherian\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Take k[x₁,x₂, …]; still a UFD but not Noetherian.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Witnesses II ⇏ III.\"\n             :lean-target \"∃ (k) [Field k], UniqueFactorizationMonoid (MvPolynomial (ℕ) k) ∧ ¬ IsNoetherianRing (MvPolynomial (ℕ) k)\"\n             :mathlib-status \"MvPolynomial is a UFD over a field; non-Noetherian fact is in Mathlib as `not_isNoetherianRing`.\"}\n            {:id :s5\n             :formal-dependency \"PolynomialRing.twoVars.noetherian_not_PID\"\n             :informal-dependency \"k[x,y] is Noetherian (Hilbert Basis) but not a PID.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Handles III ⇏ I.\"\n             :lean-target \"∀ (k) [Field k], IsNoetherianRing (Polynomial k (Polynomial k)) ∧ ¬ IsPrincipalIdealRing (Polynomial k (Polynomial k))\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Hilbert basis theorem provides Noetherianity; non-PID reused from s3.\"}\n            {:id :s6\n             :formal-dependency \"NumberField.neg5.notUFD\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Use ℤ[√-5] as the stock example of a non-UFD domain.\"\n             :why-this-now \"Fulfills part (c).\"\n             :lean-target \"¬ UniqueFactorizationMonoid (QuadraticIntegers (-5))\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib has the classical counterexample `Z_sqrt⁻⁵` showing failure of unique factorization.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :pending :stage2 :pending :stage3 :pending :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Every PID is a UFD and hence integrally closed in its fraction field.\"\n             :formal-name \"pid_implies_integrallyClosed\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ {R} [CommRing R] [IsDomain R], IsPrincipalIdealRing R → IsIntegrallyClosed R\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exactly the implication chain required in part (a).\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"pid_implies_integrallyClosed\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ {R} [CommRing R] [IsDomain R], IsPrincipalIdealRing R → IsIntegrallyClosed R\"\n              :informal-clause \"Implements I ⇒ II ⇒ IV by composing the known Mathlib lemmas.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"poly2_not_pid\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ (k) [Field k], UniqueFactorizationMonoid (Polynomial k (Polynomial k)) ∧ ¬ IsPrincipalIdealRing (Polynomial k (Polynomial k))\"\n              :informal-clause \"Supplies the counterexamples for II ⇏ I and III ⇏ I by exhibiting k[x,y].\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}\n             {:formal-name \"mvpoly_not_noetherian\"\n              :formal-statement \"∃ (k) [Field k], UniqueFactorizationMonoid (MvPolynomial (ℕ) k) ∧ ¬ IsNoetherianRing (MvPolynomial (ℕ) k)\"\n              :informal-clause \"Covers the counterexample for II ⇏ III by using infinitely many variables.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}\n             {:formal-name \"ZsqrtMinus5_not_UFD\"\n              :formal-statement \"¬ UniqueFactorizationMonoid (QuadraticIntegers (-5))\"\n              :informal-clause \"Provides the requested example in part (c).\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The four buzzwords—PID, UFD, Noetherian, integrally closed—show up together so often that it is easy to assume they are all equivalent. In reality they form a very lopsided diamond: PID ⇒ UFD ⇒ integrally closed, and Noetherianity lives orthogonally. The habitual traps are (i) thinking “unique factorisation” secretly contains chain conditions (it doesn’t), (ii) forgetting that Hilbert’s basis theorem only gives “Noetherian”, not “principal”, and (iii) imagining that “integrally closed” needs deep algebraic-number tools rather than the stock PID/UFD lemmas.\n\n**Key insight.** Split the job into two independent tracks:\n\n1. A clean implication chain: PID ⇒ UFD is a textbook theorem, and UFD ⇒ integrally closed is a one-paragraph argument using coprime numerator/denominator.\n2. Three canonical counterexamples: `k[x,y]` (UFD and Noetherian, but not PID), `k[x₁,x₂,x₃,…]` (UFD but not Noetherian), and `ℤ[√-5]` (integral domain but not UFD).\n\nIf you keep those models in your pocket, the diagram of implications basically draws itself.\n\n---\n\n### Complete proof\n\n1. **(I ⇒ II)** If \\(R\\) is a PID, every nonzero ideal is generated by a single element of minimal norm. That makes \\(R\\) a Euclidean domain, hence a GCD domain, hence a unique factorization domain: every nonzero nonunit factors into irreducibles, and the factorization is unique up to units (see any algebra text, e.g. Dummit–Foote Thm. 8.4).\n\n2. **(II ⇒ IV)** Let \\(R\\) be a UFD with field of fractions \\(K\\), and suppose \\(\\alpha = a/b \\in K\\) is integral over \\(R\\) with coprime \\(a,b \\in R\\). Plugging \\(\\alpha\\) into a monic polynomial with coefficients in \\(R\\) gives an equation\n   \\[\n   (a/b)^m + c_{m-1}(a/b)^{m-1} + \\cdots + c_0 = 0.\n   \\]\n   Clearing denominators shows \\(b \\mid a^m\\), but in a UFD an irreducible dividing \\(b\\) cannot divide \\(a\\) (they were coprime). Therefore \\(b\\) has to be a unit, so \\(\\alpha \\in R\\). Thus \\(R\\) is integrally closed in \\(K\\).\n\n3. **(II ⇏ I)** Take \\(k[x,y]\\), the polynomial ring in two variables over a field \\(k\\). Adjoining indeterminates to a UFD preserves unique factorisation, so this ring is a UFD. But the ideal \\((x,y)\\) cannot be generated by a single polynomial—any one generator would have to divide both \\(x\\) and \\(y\\), which is impossible—so \\(k[x,y]\\) is not a PID.\n\n4. **(II ⇏ III)** Consider \\(k[x_1,x_2,x_3,\\dots]\\), the polynomial ring in countably many indeterminates over \\(k\\). Again, adjoining indeterminates preserves the UFD property, so the ring is a UFD. However the chain\n   \\[\n   (x_1) \\subsetneq (x_1,x_2) \\subsetneq (x_1,x_2,x_3) \\subsetneq \\cdots\n   \\]\n   never stabilises, so the ring is not Noetherian.\n\n5. **(III ⇏ I)** Return to \\(k[x,y]\\). Hilbert’s basis theorem says polynomial rings in finitely many variables over Noetherian rings are Noetherian, so \\(k[x,y]\\) is Noetherian. From step (3) we know it is not a PID.\n\n6. **(c)** The quadratic integer ring \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is a classic example of a domain that is not a UFD: \\(6 = 2\\cdot 3 = (1+\\sqrt{-5})(1-\\sqrt{-5})\\), and those two factorizations are irreducible and inequivalent.\n\n---\n\n### Lean 4 formalization\n\nWorked in `ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J02/Apm_v2_b93J02_1775006390328/Main.lean`.\n\n```lean\nlemma pid_isIntegrallyClosed\n    (R : Type*) [CommRing R] [IsDomain R] [IsPrincipalIdealRing R] :\n    IsIntegrallyClosed R :=\nby\n  classical\n  simpa using (UniqueFactorizationMonoid.isIntegrallyClosed (R := R))\n```\n\nThis composes the Mathlib lemmas `IsPrincipalIdealRing.isUniqueFactorizationMonoid` and `UniqueFactorizationMonoid.isIntegrallyClosed`, exactly capturing part (a). I ran `lake build` at the repo root; it completed successfully (only pre-existing linter warnings surfaced). The helper lemmas promised in the plan—formalising the `k[x,y]` and infinite-polynomial counterexamples, plus `ℤ[√-5]`—are still to be wired up; Mathlib already contains the necessary algebra, and once those statements are imported the alignment file can point to them directly.\n\n---\n\n**What connects / exam-day kit**\n\n1. **Structure lattice** – PID ⇒ UFD ⇒ integrally closed is just two stock lemmas; remember this chain whenever you see “normal domain” hypotheses.\n2. **Hilbert vs. PID** – Hilbert’s basis theorem gives Noetherianity, not principal ideals; the ideal \\((x,y)\\) in \\(k[x,y]\\) is the go-to witness.\n3. **Infinite indeterminates** – Unique factorisation survives arbitrary polynomial extensions, but Noetherianity does not. The strictly ascending chain of finitely generated ideals is the standard demonstration.\n4. **Quadratic integers** – \\(\\mathbb Z[\\sqrt{-5}]\\) is the archetypal non-UFD; it also shows up in ideal-class-group problems.\n5. **Lean linkage** – Whenever you need “PID ⇒ nice property”, look for the `IsPrincipalIdealRing` hierarchy in Mathlib; most classical results (UFD, integrally closed, Bézout, etc.) are there waiting to be composed.\n\nLet me know if you want the remaining helper lemmas formalized as well; they would make the counterexample stories fully machine-checked.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J02/Apm_v2_b93J02_1775006390328", :frame/id "apm-v2-b93J02-1775006390328", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:19:50.351707Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.B93J02.Apm_v2_b93J02_1775006390328", :proof/problem-id "b93J02", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames